# Python Quality, Packaging, and Typing

## Python Standards

### Code Quality
- Use PEP 8 style guidelines
- Maximum line length: 88 characters (Black formatter)
- Use type hints for all function parameters and return values
- Implement proper error handling with custom exceptions
- Follow DRY principle and avoid code duplication

### Project Structure
```
project/
├── src/
│   └── package_name/
│       ├── __init__.py
│       ├── main.py
│       └── modules/
├── tests/
│   ├── __init__.py
│   ├── test_main.py
│   └── fixtures/
├── docs/
├── requirements.txt
├── pyproject.toml
├── setup.py (optional)
└── README.md
```

### Dependencies Management
- Use `pyproject.toml` for modern Python packaging
- Pin dependency versions for reproducibility
- Separate dev and production dependencies
- Use virtual environments (venv/conda)
- Regularly update dependencies and check for vulnerabilities

### Type Hints & Static Analysis
- Use `typing` module for complex types
- Implement dataclasses for data structures
- Use mypy for static type checking
- Configure strict type checking in CI/CD

### Testing Framework
- Use pytest for unit and integration tests
- Implement fixtures for test data
- Aim for >80% code coverage
- Write descriptive test names and docstrings
- Use parameterized tests for similar scenarios

### Logging & Monitoring
- Use Python's logging module with appropriate levels
- Implement structured logging (JSON format)
- Add request IDs for tracing
- Monitor key metrics and performance indicators

### Security Best Practices
- Validate all inputs and sanitize outputs
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Implement proper authentication and authorization
- Store secrets securely (environment variables, key vaults)
- Regularly update dependencies for security patches

### Performance Optimization
- Profile code to identify bottlenecks
- Use appropriate data structures and algorithms
- Implement caching where beneficial
- Optimize database queries and connections
- Consider async/await for I/O operations